# Stage README Standard: Technical Blog + Demo Guide

Each stage README is an educational artifact first and an operational note second. Readers should understand the "why, what, how, and so what" of the stage even if they never install the demo.

The writing should loosely follow a tell-show-tell presentation flow in the background, but **never expose methodology labels** such as "Tell" or "Show" in the README.

## Primary Audience

Write for enterprise architects, solution architects, platform engineers, and developer experience teams evaluating Red Hat OpenShift AI for regulated or security-sensitive software development use cases, especially hybrid cloud environments in European enterprises where privacy, sovereignty, and governance are first-order design concerns.

Assume many readers:
- Work in large organizations with privacy, sovereignty, and governance requirements.
- Need to understand why public AI services are not always acceptable for source code.
- Want to see how Red Hat products and open source projects combine into an enterprise platform.
- May only read the README and never run the lab.
- Care about general enterprise architecture patterns more than demo-only sequencing.

## Narrative Principles

Every stage README must explain:

- **Why this matters** - the enterprise problem or architectural concern.
- **What this stage adds** - the platform capability introduced by the stage.
- **What to notice and why it matters** - the essential demo proof points and their enterprise significance.
- **How Red Hat and open source make it work** - product layer plus upstream/open source layer.
- **Where it fits** - how this stage connects to the full workshop.

Lead with this repository's demo storyline, not with a quoted external article, vendor blog, or product documentation summary. External references should support and validate the story after the reader understands what this stage does in the workshop.

Before rewriting stage README narrative, read the stage's `## References` links that are relevant to the affected content, prioritizing official Red Hat product pages and documentation. Use that source material to align terminology and product positioning, but keep the README voice focused on this demo and its enterprise architecture pattern.

Each stage should make continuity explicit without making the section read like a teaser for later labs:
- What the previous stage made possible.
- What this stage adds to the trusted enterprise AI platform.
- Why the capability matters for private and governed AI coding assistance.
- How the capability fits into the overall platform pattern.

When aligning to Red Hat recommendations, use Red Hat guidance as the implementation baseline and reference material. Do not write as if the README exists to summarize a Red Hat article. The README should tell our demo story while using Red Hat terminology, product positioning, and documented implementation patterns.

Do not lead with YAML, commands, or implementation details. Commands belong in `Deploy And Validate` and should be secondary.

README files are educational technical articles, not runbooks. Move operational sequences to `docs/OPERATIONS.md` and failure recovery to `docs/TROUBLESHOOTING.md`. Keep implementation claims aligned with GitOps manifests, deploy scripts, validation scripts, and examples. Future capabilities must be labeled as future work, and trust boundaries, credentials, external services, and data movement must be explicit.

## Required Structure

Use this section pattern unless there is a strong reason not to:

```markdown
# Stage NNN: Capability Name

## Why This Matters

## Architecture

![Stage NNN layered capability map](../../docs/assets/architecture/stage-NNN-capability-map.svg)

## What This Stage Adds

## What To Notice And Why It Matters

## How Red Hat And Open Source Make It Work

## Trust Boundaries
<!-- Include when data boundary, privacy, identity, or external services matter. -->

## Red Hat Products Used

## Open Source Projects To Know

## Where This Fits In The Full Platform

## Deploy And Validate

## References

## Next Stage
```

Use natural blog-style prose. Do not make the README feel like a checklist unless the section is explicitly operational.

## Merged Notice And WHY Section

The `## What To Notice And Why It Matters` section replaces the older separate `What To Notice In The Demo` and `Why This Is Worth Knowing` sections.

This section should be concise and useful for architects and platform engineers. It should:

- Start with the main capability or platform control introduced by the stage.
- Highlight the most important demo proof points, preferably in three to five bullets.
- Explain why the capability matters for enterprise-grade AI in hybrid cloud environments.
- Use official Red Hat product terminology and avoid informal shorthand when the product name matters.
- Make privacy, sovereignty, identity, quota, telemetry, credential, or external-provider boundaries explicit when relevant.
- Favor general enterprise use cases over references to later stages in the workshop.

Avoid:

- Repeating every item from `What This Stage Adds`.
- Turning the section into a deployment checklist.
- Over-emphasizing future work or planned later-stage consumption.
- Claiming regulatory compliance; describe architecture controls and choices instead.

## What This Stage Adds Section

The `## What This Stage Adds` section should summarize the platform capability introduced by the stage. It is not a manifest inventory, deployment trace, or workaround ledger.

Use this shape:

```markdown
## What This Stage Adds

This stage adds <one-sentence platform capability>.

- <Capability area 1>, described in product/platform terms.
- <Capability area 2>, especially identity, policy, quota, telemetry, trust boundary, or consumption model when relevant.
- <Capability area 3>, naming CRs or implementation details only when they are important teaching concepts.
- <Capability area 4>, if needed.
```

Keep this section concise:

- Prefer four to six bullets.
- Use official Red Hat product terminology.
- Explain capabilities at the platform level before naming resource kinds.
- Use resource names only when they are user-visible, architecturally important, or important teaching concepts.
- Avoid linking to individual manifest files in every bullet; the `Deploy And Validate` section already links to the stage manifest directory.
- Move operational caveats, validation behavior, and workaround detail to `docs/OPERATIONS.md`, `docs/TROUBLESHOOTING.md`, or `BACKLOG.md` unless they change the architecture story.
- Avoid repeating the full `What To Notice And Why It Matters` explanation. `What This Stage Adds` says what appears; the next section says why it matters.

Do not include low-level implementation details such as:

- Per-file GitOps paths or one link per bullet.
- YAML field paths such as `spec.*` unless the field is the capability being taught.
- Probe timings, patch jobs, sync hooks, or generated resource names.
- Validation script behavior except when the validation behavior is itself part of the stage capability.

## Red Hat Product Demo Requirements

This is a Red Hat product demo. Every stage README must clearly identify the relevant Red Hat products and explain their role.

Examples:
- **Red Hat OpenShift** - platform substrate: Kubernetes, identity, RBAC, networking, routes, scheduling, monitoring.
- **Red Hat OpenShift AI** - AI platform, GenAI Studio, dashboard, model registry, model serving, MaaS.
- **Red Hat OpenShift GitOps** - declarative delivery and Argo CD reconciliation.
- **Red Hat OpenShift Dev Spaces** - managed cloud development workspaces.
- **Migration Toolkit for Applications** - application modernization analysis and developer workflow.
- **Developer Lightspeed for MTA** - AI-assisted modernization.
- **Red Hat Developer Hub** - enterprise developer portal and software catalog.
- **Red Hat Connectivity Link** - API connectivity, gateway policy, and rate-limit enforcement.
- **Red Hat build of Keycloak** - supported identity broker where used.

Use official Red Hat product names. Avoid generic descriptions when the product name matters.

## Open Source Education Requirements

Each stage should teach the important upstream projects behind the product layer. Keep this concise and practical.

Examples:
- Open Data Hub and models-as-a-service
- KServe
- vLLM
- llm-d
- Gateway API
- Kuadrant
- Authorino
- Eclipse Che and DevWorkspace
- Continue
- OpenCode
- Konveyor, Kantra, Kai
- Backstage and TechDocs

Explain what each project contributes. Do not just list links.

## Trust Boundary Language

Be precise about privacy and external providers.

Trust boundary sections should be short: one focused paragraph, maximum. Put operational credential details, patch behavior, validation behavior, and workaround history in `docs/OPERATIONS.md`, `docs/TROUBLESHOOTING.md`, or `BACKLOG.md`.

Approved language:
- "Private local models keep prompts and code inside the OpenShift platform boundary."
- "Governed external models are centrally controlled, but prompts are still processed by the external provider."
- "MaaS provides consistent access, authentication, rate limiting, and visibility across private and external model paths."
- "The platform supports governance and traceability needs for regulated organizations."
- "The architecture supports data-sovereignty choices and EU AI Act readiness through controls such as access governance, traceability, documentation, human review, and clear provider boundaries."

Avoid:
- "All AI traffic is private" when external models are present.
- "No code leaves the organization" unless the statement is explicitly limited to local/private model paths.
- Claims of EU AI Act compliance. Say the architecture supports controls, readiness, and choices relevant to regulated organizations.

## References Requirements

Each README must include:
- Official Red Hat documentation or product pages relevant to the stage.
- Important upstream/open source project documentation.
- Any implementation-specific references used to justify design choices.

Prefer official docs over blogs unless the blog is the authoritative context for the demo.

## Architecture Diagram Convention

Each stage README includes an SVG architecture diagram under a `## Architecture` heading. The diagram is placed **after** "Why This Matters" and **before** "What This Stage Adds" — the reader first understands the motivation, then sees the visual, then reads the specifics.

- Diagrams live in `docs/assets/architecture/` and are named `stage-NNN-capability-map.svg`.
- Use a markdown image reference: `![Stage NNN layered capability map](../../docs/assets/architecture/stage-NNN-capability-map.svg)`
- Do not place the diagram at the top of the file or before the title.
- The `## Architecture` heading makes the diagram linkable and visible in the table of contents.
- Stage diagrams must use the same architecture layers and capability list as the root diagram. The stage diagram changes only visual state: capabilities introduced in that stage are highlighted, previously introduced capabilities remain readable, and not-yet-introduced capabilities are dimmed.
- Regenerate root and stage architecture diagrams with `node scripts/generate-architecture-diagrams.mjs` instead of hand-editing individual SVG files.

Current diagram design:
- Use the same Layout B layered table as the root diagram: product rail, logical layer labels, and capability boxes.
- The product rail uses Red Hat palette colors: purple for **Red Hat Advanced Developer Suite**, teal for **Red Hat OpenShift AI**, and Red Hat red for **Red Hat OpenShift**.
- The table uses a transparent outer SVG canvas with dark neutral panels, gray borders, white text, and stage-highlight borders.
- Root capability boxes use a dark fill with a product-colored left stripe; stage diagrams reuse that treatment for previously introduced capabilities.
- Stage diagrams distinguish capability state: new capabilities use a heavy product-colored border, previously introduced capabilities use a dark fill with a product-colored left stripe, and not-yet-introduced capabilities are dimmed.
- The logical layers must stay in this order:
  - Developer productivity and modernization
  - Model and context choices
  - AI experiences and governed access
  - GPU acceleration and workload management
  - Container platform services
  - Infrastructure and trust boundaries
- The developer layer uses two rows: product surfaces on top, AI-assisted capabilities below.
- Do not hand-add stage-specific boxes. If a stage needs a new capability, add it to `scripts/generate-architecture-diagrams.mjs` so the root and all stage diagrams stay synchronized.
- Keep labels compact and Red Hat-aligned; avoid manifest-level implementation names unless the specific resource is the capability being taught.

## Markdown Style

- Use sequential heading levels.
- Use `-` for unordered lists.
- Use fenced code blocks with language identifiers.
- Use relative links for repo files.
- Use descriptive link text; never use bare URLs.
- Prefer SVG architecture diagrams from `docs/assets/architecture/` over inline ASCII diagrams.
- Keep operational commands copy-pastable but secondary.

## Agent Behavior

After modifying a stage README:
- Verify no literal "Tell:" or "Show:" labels remain.
- Verify the opening leads with the demo storyline and does not start by summarizing an external article or product document.
- Verify `What This Stage Adds` uses one capability sentence plus roughly four to six capability bullets.
- Verify `What This Stage Adds` is concise, capability-oriented, and not a low-level manifest inventory, deployment trace, or workaround ledger.
- Verify `What This Stage Adds` avoids per-bullet manifest links, YAML field paths, probe timings, patch jobs, sync hooks, and generated resource names unless they are central teaching concepts.
- Verify section order places `What To Notice And Why It Matters` after `What This Stage Adds` and before `How Red Hat And Open Source Make It Work`.
- Verify `Trust Boundaries`, when present, appears before `Red Hat Products Used`.
- Verify the merged section preserves the essential demo proof points and the enterprise WHY without becoming verbose.
- Verify the merged section is written for enterprise architects and platform engineers in regulated environments, with privacy, sovereignty, and hybrid cloud considerations where relevant.
- Verify the merged section favors general enterprise use cases over references to capabilities planned for later stages.
- Verify relevant Red Hat reference links were read before rewriting product-positioning language.
- Verify Red Hat product coverage is explicit.
- Verify open source projects are explained where relevant.
- Verify `Trust Boundaries` is one focused paragraph when present.
- Verify privacy statements distinguish private local models from governed external models and MCP/tool context boundaries.
- Verify EU AI Act language is framed as readiness/supporting controls, not legal compliance.
- Verify `Deploy And Validate`, `References`, and `Next Stage` exist.
- Run `git diff --check`.
